Barack Obama receives the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth US President
American President Barack Obama is coming to Oslo, Norway for 26 hours to receive the Nobel Peace Prize here as the fourth US President in history.
In addition, he receives the diploma, the medal and a cheque of $1.4 million for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among peoples.
The head of the White House arrives tomorrow together with his wife Michelle in the Northweg metropolis and will be busy all the time.
First of all, he visits the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time with the five committee members who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organisations.
The Presidential couple then planned a meeting with Norwegian King Harald V. and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit reaches its climax with the ceremony at which Obama takes over the prestigious prize.
He is the fourth president of the United States, but only the third to receive the prize directly in office.
The White House has already indicated that Obama will talk about the war in Afghanistan when he took over the prize.
The President does not want to avoid this issue because he knows that he will take the prize as a President who is currently at war in two countries.
A few days ago, he reinforced the war effort by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the Golmedaille, the diploma and the cheque for ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate the money for charitable purposes, but he has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The event program then includes a banquet with the President and his wife, at which, besides Norway's King and Queen, the Prime Minister and a further 250 invited guests will be present.
Obama was very cautious about the price from the beginning.
He said, for example, that he felt that he was not entirely earning the prize.
He also repeated several times that the price is not only for him, but for all those who strive for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he stated that this is "a call for action" for him.
