Czech discovery: a substance that also works with ́stamped ́ HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works with viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact predominates against the disadvantage that the compound does not have as much effect on common virus variants as one of the already existing medicines.
The disease AIDS cannot yet be cured.
The patient can, however, prolong life and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, your intake is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of virus proliferation also results in the development of resistance viruses, which are no longer effective.
The work of the experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, from VSCHT (Chemical and Technological University) Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to dealing with virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances referred to as metalocarborans have an effect on the protein that is responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
The metalokarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the virus increase in a different way than any medicine used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new ́improved ́ compounds, which were prepared on the basis of the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding on the virus protein.
The metalokarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-faceted cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Insidious and persistent virus
HIV protease is the protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus split caused by HIV protease, no mature infection virus particles would arise.
When we eliminate HIV protease, we also eliminate the proliferation of the virus in the patient's body, explain the scientists in the press report published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the work published in the journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically changed further.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of these series of substances against HIV protease was tested in the test tube, also against their resistant (resistant) variants obtained from HIV infected patients.
The effect of the metalokarboranes on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as in the clinically used medicines, but it does not lose its effect on the resistance variants, against which the used drugs are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action as well as its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical design, makes the metalocarborans interesting for further research aimed at the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, Head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology of the Institutes of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
