The ice that characterizes it melts at alarming speed and takes life with it, which cannot survive anywhere else.
Oil, gas, shipping and fishing interests have recently entered open waters, with diplomats, lawyers and now also writers in their keel water.
Richard Ellis, an author and illustrator, draws in "On thin ice" (original title: "On Thin Ice") a natural history of the icon of the north, the polar bear.
Immersed in the complicated history and politics of whaling, he describes the long tradition of Arctic researchers who have proved themselves in hunting the polar bears.
Admiral Nelson's encounter with a polar bear as a brave 14-year-old ensign at sea, who only fought with the rifle butt of his musket, is certainly a legend, but others are true.
Young bears caught swimming behind the bodies of their recently killed mothers were taken to zoos and circuses.
A circus performance at the beginning of the 20th century showed 75 polar bears at one performance.
Even today, zoos still typically have one millionth of the life range of a wild old animal. The climate is rarely suitable: the polar bear in Singapore became quite green from the algae that grow in the hollow hair of its fur.
