Ellis refers to the reports of other authors and historians and often returns to the threat that hunters pose to the survival of the species.
Although forbidden in Norway, America and Russia, killing continues in Greenland and Canada, where hunters in helicopters and snowmobile-riding Inuit use powerful assault rifles to hunt down their prey.
Ironically, the ice will remain the longest in the waters in the north of these two hunting nations.
In his new book "After the Ice", Alun Anderson, a former editor of the science magazine "New Scientist", offers a clear and disturbing description of the science of the Arctic and a gripping insight into how the future could develop.
Not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither atmospheric scientists nor oceanographers can adequately explain the speed of change.
But that is not because of a lack of explanations.
The pioneer journeys of Fridtjof Nansen at the end of the 19th and early 20th centuries for the first time let us guess the turbulence of the pack ice.
Undersea boats in the Cold War the shifting ridges while sailing down.
A useful addition is satellite surveying and the large-scale application of probes on icebergs, but still much is achieved by intrepid people camping outside in the cold.
Anderson takes a look at the peculiar, tiny world of the inflow system within the Arctic ice formed by saltwater channel compressed during freezing.
But, from the bear on the ice to the microscopic miracles in the ice, all of them are threatened when the summer ice passes, which is expected between 2013 and 2050.
