Marine infantry workers were among the 6,000 who laid wreaths in Arlington
The Superior Private De'Angello Robinson travelled by bus for seven hours to lay a single wreath on the grave of a soldier he had never met.
For him and the other naval infantrymen who traveled from Camp Johnson in Jacksonville, North Carolina to the National Cemetery in Arlington to decorate graves, the day was a tribute to the men and women in whose footsteps they followed.
In a few months, from where we're being brought back, we could be, Robinson said about the fallen soldiers.
If we were, I'd wish someone would do the same for me, so I'm trying to show my respect.
He was one of more than 6,000 volunteers who gathered on Saturday morning to lay wreaths on the graves of veterans in several sections of the Arlington Cemetery.
Morrill Worcester, owner of Worcester Wreath Company in Harrington, Maine, founded this tradition in 1992, when he and some others decided to decorate several hundred graves in the Arlington cemetery.
It is now an 18-year-old tradition and Morrill and his wife Karen, who make this trip every year, stop in different cities along the way to carry out events dedicated to people in the military and victims of terrorism.
The Worcesters also founded a non-profit organization, Wreaths Across America, which extended the event to other countries.
This year, volunteers laid more than 16,000 wreaths on the graves in the Arlington Cemetery, in areas at the Pentagon, on the graves of the Fayetteville National Cemetery in Arkansas, in Battery Park in New York, and at the United Airlines Flight 93 memorial site in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
For the second time, the Walmart Foundation donated more than $150,000 to purchase and transport the wreaths.
Charleen Hunt, 70, from Westminster, said that she made the trip to Arlington in memory of her husband, a deceased professional soldier.
Although her husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said this is her way to give back to those who made sacrifices.
She said this is a small contribution to helping civilians our soldiers.
It's like visiting a family graveyard.
Packed in layers of warm clothing, the volunteers wandered across the extensive lawns and hills of the cemetery.
The volunteers had older graves from the 1st and 2nd World War and the Vietnam War as their goal, as these are not visited as often as the newer graves, according to the organizers.
The mood was cheerful, children played and couples held their hands while they carried the fresh pine branches to the graying tombstones.
Each round wreath was dark green with a small red loop attached to the upper part.
Section 60, which is nearby and where mainly veterans of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried, remained almost calm.
The United Service Organizations donated 1,000 wreaths to decorate this section, but the gloomy mood of the current wars filled this area.
Individuals cried openly, others prayed, and families and friends clung to each other in the icy air.
Some read loudly the names carved in stone, while others bowed down to small black and white square cards, which had been put in the damp mud for those whose gravestones had not yet been completed.
Sandra Lockwood was one of the many mothers who shed bitter tears before her son's grave.
She drove 8 hours from Zanesfield, Ohio, to visit the tomb of naval infrastructure sergeant David Shane Spicer, who fell in combat in July.
No one should ever forget why we're free... my son paid for it, she said.
"When I haven't been here for a long time, I want someone to remember him."
U.S. government contractor arrested by Cuban authorities
The Cuban government has arrested a contractor from the U.S. government who sold mobile phones and notebook computers in the country, said representatives of the State Department on Saturday.
The contractor, who has not yet been identified, works for Development Alternatives Inc., based in Bethesda.
The company is working on projects for customers such as USAID, the U.S. Agency for International Development and the World Bank.
Consular officials from the U.S. Interest Group in Havana are trying to gain access to the prisoner who was arrested on December 5th.
The specific charges have not yet been published, although under Cuban law a Cuban citizen or a foreign visitor can be arrested for almost anything under the charge of "hazard".
All so-called counterrevolutionary activities, including slight protests and critical writings, pose a risk of arrest.
Anti-government graffiti and statements are considered serious crimes.
Cuba has a growing blogger community led by popular reporter Yoani Sánchez, who often describes how she and her husband are being persecuted and attacked by government officials.
Sánchez has repeatedly requested permission to leave the country to receive prices, but this has always been rejected.
The arrest of an American contractor is likely to increase tensions between the Castro brother's communist government in Cuba and the Obama administration, which had sought a "slow" approach to improving relations with the island.
The news of the arrest was first reported Friday night by the New York Times.
The new US policy attaches importance to the fact that the United States will make a contribution if the Cuban government takes concrete steps in this direction, such as the release of political prisoners and the creation of more room for opposition.
Mobile phones and notebooks are legal in Cuba, although they are new and sought-after products in a country where the average salary of a government employee is 15 dollars a month.
The Cuban government has only been allowing ordinary citizens to buy a mobile phone this year; they are used primarily for sending text messages, as a 15-minute telephone call would cost a daily wage.
Internet usage on the island is extremely limited.
It is accessible in expensive hotels and there for foreign visitors and at some government offices, such as universities.
Cubans who wish to log in often have to report their names to the government.
Access to many websites is restricted.
In Cuba, the arrest of an American is rare.
Most of the few U.S. citizens who are in prison in Cuba are behind bars for crimes such as drug smuggling, said Gloria Berbena, the press spokesman for the U.S. interest representation in Havana.
Berbena said she couldn't give any more information about the arrest.
The arrest and detention are clearly wrong.
An activity that would be legal in any other free society - giving free mobile phones - is a crime in Cuba, said Jose Miguel Vivanco, head of the American section of the Human Rights Watch group, who recently published a hard report on freedom in Cuba entitled "New Castro, Same Cuba", an allusion to Raul Castro's appointment as leader of the country, replacing the sick older brother Fidel.
Vivanco said that the defendants were very often arrested, sentenced and detained within one day.
He said that any solution would probably be political and that the Cuban government often provokes a negative reaction in the United States, especially at the time when both countries are moving towards more dialogue.
Pakistani government officials reveal plan to send men to Afghanistan
Pakistani authorities discovered on Saturday a supposedly leading head of a conspiracy aimed at sending five men from northern Virginia to Afghanistan to kill US soldiers, and said that they hoped this case could help uncover an extensive network of terrorist recruiters searching the Internet for radicalized young men.
Investigators said that they had been looking for an opaque insurgent known as Saifullah, who had invited the men to Pakistan after he had found them because one of them on the YouTube video page had made positive comments on terrorist attacks.
After arriving in Pakistan, Saifullah became the leader of these men and tried to help them reach the remote area in Pakistan's tribal belt, home to Al Qaeda and his terrorist training camps.
But a representative of Pakistan's intelligence department, who was briefed on the matter, said on Saturday, Saifullah could not convince the Al Qaeda leaders that the men are not part of a CIA conspiracy to infiltrate the terrorist network.
As a result, they were detained for days in the eastern city of Sargodha, far from the inhospitable mountains in the northwest, which have become a terrorist refuge.
They were considered part of a covert operation.
Therefore, they were rejected, said the government official, who wanted to remain anonymous due to the sensitivity of the matter.
The government official said that the men were by no means discouraged and continued to seek the right recommendations to gain access to the Al Qaeda camps when they were arrested by Pakistani prison authorities.
The case of the five men - who remain in Pakistan and are questioned by the FBI - underlines the crucial role of recruiters in identifying future terrorists and perhaps even more important in deciding who is trustworthy.
Since the attacks of September 11, 2001, U.S. intelligence has made it a matter of utmost urgency to place human assets within Al Qaeda.
The recruiters of the organization act as porters who do not let in those whose commitment to the Holy War is not serious enough and those who might be spies.
American would-be recruits are subject to a special review by A Qaeda, analysts said.
However, due to their potential access to US targets and their propaganda value, they are also considered to be tremendously attractive to the group.
Evan Kohlmann, senior analyst of the NEFA Foundation based in the USA, said that terrorist groups have also become much more cautious in recent years with regard to who they allow access to, because the US intelligence services have become experts in their recruitment methods.
If you try to get someone into these groups, what better way could you go than to follow the recruitment model that so many have already followed?, Kohlmann said.
The model is now much more based on the Internet.
Tens of thousands of demonstrators call for climate action in Copenhagen
Tens of thousands of demonstrators marched through the streets here on Saturday and demanded more bold action on climate protection from the negotiators at the Bella Congress Centre in the city.
Demonstrators said that 100,000 people had joined the event, while police estimates were more likely to be based on about 25,000.
The event was relatively peaceful, although a handful of masked activists lit small explosives near some government buildings in downtown.
On a day when little happened during the UN-sponsored climate negotiations, thousands of activists wandered through the city with banners saying "There is no Planet B" in English and one in Spanish, saying "The Earth says "Enough".
Some stars joined the protest, for example the Danish model, the photographer Helena Christensen, who said that the journeys to Peru, her mother's country of birth, made her aware of the heartbreaking problems facing the country due to the already noticeable effects of climate change.
That is part of the motivation why I decided to take part in the big demonstration - to pass on the word and appeal to the world leaders to bring about a fair, ambitious and binding agreement, she said.
It is not an easy task, but it must be done now and there is no way around it.
The police prevented the demonstrators from getting too close to the Bella Centre and said they had arrested 19 people, mainly because they were either masked or carrying pocket knives.
According to Danish law, these actions are prohibited during demonstrations.
According to a spectator who did not want to be called because he was involved in the climate negotiations, masked demonstrators in black clothes set fire to several explosive devices near the Copenhagen main canal, near which several ministries are located.
They threw them near the buildings, he said, adding that they began as flares, but then followed by "a few big explosions."
Inside the convention center, people gathered in front of TV screens to watch the demonstration all afternoon.
But the protest did not seem to have reached the awareness of the main officials, such as Su Wie, China's chief climate negotiator.
When asked if he thought that the demonstration had a constructive effect on international considerations, he replied in English: "This is something I was not even aware of."
He then went on to Mandarin and said, "Because the venue is big, I can't hear what's happening outside."
He noted that it depended on the individual's perspective whether the demonstration would harm or help.
It shows the focus of the general public and various sectors on the topic of climate change, he said.
On the other hand, "one can also say that they disturb the negotiations or the freedom of other people".
Test data show persistent race gap
The testimonies on mathematics performance were last week welcome good news for the public schools in Washington D.C.
Although Washington District is still far behind the country's high-performance schools, the testimonies show that the fourth and eighth graders have made faster progress in the past two years than cities that include Atlanta, Chicago, and New York.
But what is included in the latest figures of National Assessment of Educational Progress (NAEP) is the persistent performance gap between African American and white students, both at local and national level.
The average score of white fourth graders from Washington D.C. has risen from 262 to 270 in the last two years (on a scale of 500), but only three points from 209 to 212 for their African-American peers.
The performance gap actually rose from 53 to 58 points between 2007 and 2009.
The progress of the Afro-American eight-graders remained basically the same, falling by a statistically negligible point from 245 to 244.
The average score of white students was not included in the test data because the sample size was not large enough.
The picture over a six-year period is also not more encouraging.
The gap that separated white and black fourth graders in 2003 when the first NAEP was captured in this district was 60 scale points (262 to 202).
And although the score that children of both groups have reached has increased over this period, the difference has hardly decreased with 58 points now.
Some of the district's educational supporters expressed their concern last week that the results celebrated by school chancellor Michelle A. Rhee and the democratic mayor Adrian M. Fenty were largely driven by white students who are already high-performing children.
This suggests that we have raised the overall ranking by treating those at the upper end of the scale, which is problematic and difficult, said Jeff Smith, board member of D.C. Voice, a non-profit group that advocates education equality in Washington D.C.
I don't jump up and down for a span of two or three points, said the Democratic Washington City Council member, Kwame R. Brown, who has a daughter in the fourth grade of the Eaton primary school.
Brown, a frequent critic of Rhee's management style, said the message of test scores is that the city's middle schools urgently need attention.
Of course, you always want to see the positive signs, I respect that.
But what scares me is that we don't spend nearly the time and energy we need to spend on our middle school.
Rhee said the district must continue to find better ways to meet the needs of low-performance students.
This fall, for example, some teachers are trained to use a new reading curriculum, the Wilson Reading System, aimed at pupils in the upper classes of primary and middle school, who have not mastered basic reading skills at the beginning of their school career and who are significantly behind their peer classmates.
Everyday mathematics, a curriculum that focuses from kindergarten to sixth grade games and lifelike experiences, was brought to Washington under the former school inspector Clifford Janey, and this curriculum is attributed to some of the NAEP advances reported last week.
I believe that we must continue to work to make the best efforts available to the students who are below the grade level, said Rhee.
Others say that NAEP results highlight the question of whether Rhee can continue to improve the overall performance of the system while continuing to provide the additional money and resources for the low-performance schools that are needed to reduce the gap.
This is a serious dilemma for Michelle Rhee, said Bruce Fuller, professor of education at the University of California at Berkeley, who investigated urban exam results.
The conventional remedy is to focus its resources and management reforms on the schools located in the poorest areas of Washington D.C.
The objective could produce political after-effects that work against this important item on the agenda.
The weak point, of course, is, as with other city school inspectors, that she is trying to keep the white and black middle class.
Our focus is to ensure that we build a system of great schools.
We need to strengthen our schools in the neighbourhoods so that all families, regardless of where they live, can be sure that their children can receive excellent public education.
Janey, who is now a school inspector in Newark, said in an interview this week that one of the most important elements of closing the performance gap is to extend the traditional public school year, which is currently 180 days in Washington, to compete with charter schools.
One has to increase the school year to approximately 200 days to have the power to change, said Janey, who came to an agreement with his teacher union last year on 185 days a year, which he considered to be "a milestone" on the way to a greater increase in the next contract.
Higher education for more people than future prospects
The coach reaches the Gettysburg-College with a loud whistle.
Graciela Rodriguez, 12, gets out and blinks for a moment at the sight of the white columns, the brick facades and the emerald green lawn.
Graciela's parents barely graduated from high school in El Salvador.
Until recently, Graciela, who was rescued in Silver Spring and now lives in Riverdale, had never set foot on a college campus.
Their attitude and that of the other eight-graders of the group who explore Gettysburg, where teaching costs 38,690 dollars a year, was more of an awe-inspiring visitor than that of an enthusiastic future student.
"Yes! I'll be here soon!" cried Graciela, who would like to study medicine, when the Führer announced that they had now entered the Science Building.
"Wow, really?" she said thoughtfully when she was told the low professor-to-student ratio of the school.
College in Pennsylvania was the 7th that the kids went to on their three-day tour, and now they've fully received the intended message: The question is not whether to go to college.
The question is where.
On the one hand, there is growing concern about the large number of children born in the United States of Hispanic immigrants who do not end high school or become pregnant as a teenager, but on the other hand there are hundreds of thousands who receive the college education needed to get into the middle class.
In fact, one of five of these "second generation" of Hispanic Americans completes college – which is a remarkable achievement, as many of their immigrated parents, mostly from Mexico or Central America, came to the United States without graduating from high school.
Their success stories are important, say researchers, because they show the way forward for a generation that will play a huge role in the country's workforce.
Those who study powerful children say that they often have a natural affinity for school and an indwelling drive to success.
Many of them also have parents who set high goals for their children and find ways to compensate for their lack of familiarity with American schools.
But counseling programs also play a major role by helping Graciela and millions of children like her to go to college, especially if these efforts persist over a long period of time.
If you look at low-income children whose parents do not have the experience and skills to help them find their way through the system, then a single measure will not solve the problem at any time, said Patricia Gándara, researcher at the University of California in Davis, who investigated Hispanic American students.
We need to think about providing these children with a supportive network from preschool to high school.
The federal program that had financed Gracielas College Tour is a useful example.
It is known as GEAR UP - To power up a gear - and provides more than $300 million per year for local school systems to start college preparation programs that start when low-income students are in middle school and continue to run until they finish high school.
According to the US Department of Education, the programme has helped more than 10 million students since 1999, more than 60% of whom have gone to college.
Iraqi Ministry of Oil signs contracts with 10 foreign oil companies
Despite concerns about violence and political instability, the Iraqi government has been able to get larger oil companies to rebuild its damaged infrastructure at two auctions closed on Saturday.
The 10 contracts signed with foreign oil companies by the Iraqi Ministry of Oil suggest that China, Russia and European oil companies are ready to play an important role in the renovation of the Iraqi oil industry, which has been paralyzed for decades by war and economic sanctions.
American companies could only account for two of the 10 auctioned fields.
Seven American companies had paid for participation in the second auction, which started on Friday.
The only company that made a bid was shortlisted.
Two American companies were able to conclude contracts for fields auctioned in June.
The thinly sown representatives of American oil multinationals surprised analysts at the opening of the Iraqi oil industry.
Iraq has finally opened its doors after 6 years of war and instead of US companies give Asian and European the way ahead, said Ruba Husari, editor of Iraq Oil Forum, an online news service.
There will be no further offers in Iraq for a long time.
Security concerns highlighted by massive coordinated bombings on Tuesday and political instability by the withdrawal of the US military have probably prevented American oil companies, analysts said, from engaging more strongly in Iraq, which has the third largest proven crude oil reserves in the world.
U.S. companies have been disadvantaged in some cases because competitors, especially the Chinese and other state-controlled energy companies, have significantly lower wage costs and are more likely to take risks because they do not have to account for shareholders.
Exxon-Mobil and Occidental Petroleum Inc. were the only American companies that could conclude contracts with the Ministry.
Major U.S. companies, such as Chevron and ConocoPhillips, which maintain close relations with the Iraqi oil ministry and have been involved with technical advice in recent years, have run out of business.
The Russian companies Lukoil and Gazprom were the main players in two of the contracts awarded this weekend.
The state-owned China National Petroleum Corporation has offered for more contracts than any other company and could go home with large packages of contracts for two larger fields.
We all know, said Assam Jihad, spokesman for the oil ministry, that China is on its way to becoming one of the greats of the world economy and a technology power.
We are convinced that the Chinese company can compete with its bidders and will fulfil its obligations towards Iraq.
Companies pre-selected for bid submission gave bids, which were then compared with the fee per barrel of oil that the Ministry was willing to pay to increase the output of each field beyond the current level.
Top planner of Al Qaeda apparently killed in Pakistan
An obvious US missile attack along the Pakistani border with Afghanistan is said to have killed a top Al Qaeda deployment planner this week, reports US counter-terrorism officials on Friday.
This would be, if it were confirmed, the second deadly attack on a high leader of the terrorist organization this autumn.
Saleh al-Somali was one of the two Arabs who, according to US sources and Pakistani authorities, were reportedly killed by a number of missiles that hit their vehicle near Miran Shah city in northern Waziristan province on Tuesday.
Local authorities reported that the missiles were fired by a type of drone used by the CIA in Pakistan's lawless tribal belt.
They drove in a white vehicle towards the Afghan border when the car was hit, an official of Pakistani civilian intelligence from Miran Shah said by telephone.
Locals suspected of belonging to the militants ran to the site and quickly took everything that was left of the "fully destroyed bodies".
The local authorities could not confirm the identity of the victims, but two representatives of the US counter-terrorism campaign gave indeterminate evidence that Somali was among the dead.
Somali was described as the leading military planner of Al Qaeda, who led operations of terrorist groups outside the Afghanistan-Pakistan region.
He was involved in conspiracy around the world, a senior official who wanted to remain anonymous and pointed to the delicate character of the US air raids on Pakistani soil.
If one assumes its central role as given, this also included planning attacks against the US and Europe.
He took strategic instructions from the top leaders of Al Qaeda and put them into operational planning for possible terrorist attacks.
The second American official said that Somali quickly ascended in the Al Qaeda hierarchy and maintained best connections to other extremist groups in the region.
He may not be known to some Americans, said the second representative of the authorities, but this by no means reduces the danger he posed to us and our allies.
If his death were confirmed, Somali would be the second leading Al Qaeda or Taliban leader killed since September when a similar attack killed Najmuddin Jalolov, the leader of a militant faction in the tribal area and three other top activists.
The pace of attacks by CIA drones has declined from an average of six operations per month to two since the summer, according to a summary of the Long War Journal, a website maintained by a non-profit organization.
The decline can be based on improved tactics by terrorist groups that have taken steps to reduce their vulnerability while brutally killing suspected informants, the site reported.
Leading UN Envoy in Kabul Will Resign
The UN leader in Afghanistan, Kai Eide, said on Friday that he would resign from his post in March, ending a stormy term that was clouded by claims of widespread corruption in the UN-backed Afghan presidential election.
Eid's departure took place when the Obama administration decided to send another 30,000 US soldiers to Afghanistan.
The UN envoy said he supported the increase in troops, but he also expressed his concern that the US military withdrawal schedule, which is scheduled to begin in 18 months, could cause other NATO governments to withdraw their forces.
We need to speed up the building of Afghan security forces, sending the right signal to the Afghans that they can trust the international community, said Eide in a telephone interview from Kabul.
The commitment must be long-term.
The Norwegian diplomat also urged the United States and other military powers to increase the number of international civilian helpers to help Afghanistan's political transition.
The military increase must correspond to an increase on the civilian side, he said.
Eide said that he did not resign, but only fulfilled an agreement made in March 2008 with his family to stay in Kabul for only two years.
He said he wanted to notify UNO
Secretary General Ban Ki-moon now forward so that he has time to provide a replacement.
What I said is that he better start looking for a successor, said Eide.
When I came here, there was a two-month vacuum between my predecessor's departure and my arrival.
According to UN representatives, Ban has begun the search for a replacement.
The UN representatives say that he has considered the Swedish-Italian-born Staffan di Mistura, who recently led the UN mission in Baghdad, and the Frenchman Jean-Marie Guéhenno, who previously led UN peace operations.
Eide's position in Afghanistan was put to the test after his former deputy, Peter W. Galbraith, had accused him in September of favoring President Hamid Karzai in the country's presidential election and covering up evidence of massive electoral fraud.
Eide has rejected all accusations, but he also said that Galbraith's accusations - which was fired - "have undoubtedly harmed the mission because there has already been a great deal of scepticism about international interference in the election."
Eide said that he recommended the appointment of a leading civilian representative to coordinate the aid measures of the American-led forces in Afghanistan.
He also urged that the UN leadership allow his successor to hire more personnel from the United States and other Western countries that donate to the Afghan mission, and said that this would strengthen their confidence in the proper use of their money.
Eide expressed his disappointment at the limitation of his forces in Afghanistan and said that the cumbersome UN recruitment regulations have undermined his ability to bring in capable people.
The UN rules are designed in such a way that since May, he said, only one person could be hired.
This is catastrophic and must not go on like this.
US Secretary of Defense Gates: Iran must expect additional sanctions
Secretary of Defense Robert M. Gates said Friday that the world powers will soon impose "significant additional sanctions" on Iran because he did not participate in talks about his nuclear plans.
Gates spoke to a group of about 300 U.S. soldiers in northern Iraq during a 7-day trip through the war zones in Afghanistan and Iraq and downplayed the prospect of a military action against the Islamic Republic of Iran.
In Iran, there are no good choices, he said in answer to a soldier's question about the likelihood of such a development.
"One of the things on my mind is, in the last six years, if we've learned something from Iraq that is unpredictable to the war."
The Obama administration is considering a package of sanctions aimed at Iran's military and political elite, but Gates has announced that some sanctions could also affect the average Iranian.
He said that a "package of positive and negative incentives" is needed "to convince the Iranian government that it is actually less protected with nuclear weapons" because "their people will suffer tremendously" from the sanctions.
On Friday, in a statement by the White House spokesman, Robert Gibbs, the American government joined the European leaders in warning that Iran must expect "believable" consequences if it does not comply with the demands of the UN Security Council and its nuclear monitoring organisation, the International Atomic Energy Agency.
Iran continues to claim that knowledge of nuclear technology should only be gained for peaceful purposes.
During talks in Geneva on 1 October, Iran said that it would resume talks to limit its nuclear program and would renounce a substantial part of its stock of enriched uranium in exchange for urgently needed nuclear fuel for its medical research reactor.
The US government has pushed for this kind of agreement to build confidence between the two parties and to gain time for negotiations.
However, Iran seems to have left negotiations on the provisional agreements since then -- in part, experts say, because the Iranian leadership is divided as to whether they should commit to the United States.
Gates said that Iran simply abandoned the international community in relation to some of the proposals they had already agreed to at the beginning of October, frankly bringing the international community, including the Russians and Chinese, together in a way that they never were in connection with important additional sanctions for Iran.
President Obama has set the 31 December deadline for Iran to respond to these proposals before continuing to pursue other options, including those that Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton once called "suppressive sanctions."
In a statement made in New York, Iran's representation at the United Nations condemned what it called "groundless and unfounded claims" by some Security Council members on Iranian nuclear activities on Thursday, saying that they are ready to continue the talks with the United States and five other world powers "to achieve an appropriate long-term solution".
Gates, who was to return to Washington last Friday, met with Iraqi Prime Minister Nuri al-Maliki in the morning before flying to the oil-rich Kurdish region in Iraq for meetings with the soldiers in Kirkuk and with Kurdish officials in Irbil.
The tensions between the Kurds and the Arab majority in Iraq continue to be high, especially with regard to borders, property rights and the distribution of public revenues.
Gates urged both sides to reduce the potential for conflict in order to prevent delays in the US plans to reduce US military strength from 115,000 to 50,000 by the end of August.
Gates also tried to dispel Kurdish concern about the forthcoming withdrawal of troops. US representatives quoted Gates, who said to Masud Barzani, President of the Kurdish regional government, "We will preserve your security, prosperity and autonomy within a united Iraq.
We will not leave you."
A change of course in aging China
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters that gave them lectures that "Mother Earth is too tired to entertain other children" and "A baby more means a grave more."
They learned these lessons so well that, as government officials in Shanghai, who suddenly began to change course this summer because of the low birth rate and the ageing population, and encouraged young couples to have more than one child, their response was immediate and final: "No way."
We have already invested all our time and energy in a child.
There's nothing left for a second child, Wang said, 31, a staff manager with an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, which has produced two generations of notoriously thick, spoiled single children, who are affectionately called "little emperors", a population crisis in the country is coming up.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple compared to 6 at the time this policy came into force, the UN
This is well above the global average of around 20 percent.
The imbalance is stronger in rich coastal cities with educated population, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-olds and older people accounted for almost 22 percent of the reported residents of Shanghai, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of the Shanghai City Population and Family Planning Commission, has said that couples of childbearing age need to have babies to "help reduce the ratio of the ageing population and alleviate the labour shortage of the future."
Shanghai will soon be "as old -- but not as rich -- as developed countries, like Japan and Sweden," she said.
A Gradual Relaxation
Recognized in the country's 1978 constitution, China's one-child policy is likely to be the most controversial injunction introduced by the ruling Communist Party to this day.
Couples who violate this policy have to expect huge fines -- up to their triple annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination in their jobs.
Chinese state representatives have attributed it to this policy that the critical use of natural land resources could be avoided, whereas human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of politics.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who already had a child to abort.
Many couples also had sexually selective abortions, resulting in an unnaturally high relationship between men and women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their attitude to one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife were single children -- and in 2007 the tone of many harsh slogans was mitigated.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Peking University Institute of Population Research, said that government officials have recently discussed more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children with one partner being an only child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births in July.
Posters that taught families to have only one child were almost overnight replaced by guidelines that describe in detail who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city council has sent out municipal employees and volunteers for family planning to visit couples at home and put leaflets under the doors.
She also asked for psychological and financial advice for those who have more than one child.
The reaction was not encouraging, said family planning representatives.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in the outdoor areas of Shanghai said that there was an upswing in the requests of couples who wanted a second child after the campaign started, the urban districts did not report any change.
For example, Huinan, with a population of 115,000, still receives only four to five applications per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the expected number of births in the city for 2010 will still be about 165,000 -- slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of the Shanghai community Caolu, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don't want more children.
They want to give the best to their first, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said that they would like to have two children and that this was also legally permitted.
But, like many Chinese, they only have a minor government health and life insurance policy.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West misjudge one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is pregnant with her first child in the seventh month.
Yes, we're being robbed of the opportunity to have more than one child.
The problem, however, is not simply a political one.
The problem is money.
Other couples give psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the head of staff, said that she only wanted a child because she was also an only child. "We were the center of the family and we were used to everyone taking care of us.
We are not used to taking care of others and do not really want to do so."
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who owns a translation company, said it more bluntly.
For middle-class parents with a double career, which reduces the birth rate, he said, it's about being successful and for that you have to be selfish.
The age group of today's 20- to 39-year-olds grew up to see their parents struggling during the early days of the Chinese capitalism experiment, and they do not want such a life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, places huge demands on parents' time.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there's the question of space -- "You have to remodel your apartment" -- and life planning -- "If the child is 9 months old, you must already have a CV for the best preschools."
Most of his friends are willing to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to achieve a higher standard of living, he said.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
UN Group drafts plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference - which has so far been characterised by wild poses and mutual accusations - set a focus again on Friday with the publication of a document which will record an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with the industrial nations facing the greatest burdens in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement on greenhouse gas regulation, has highlighted both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But he was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time as more than 100 top politicians from all over the world will arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, formulated by a specially created UN working group, is silent about the amount of money that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how industrial and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions and how high the upper limit of the global temperature rise that policy makers would support.
The process is being given great flexibility, says John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who has drafted the six-page document, has summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's leading climate protection representative, Yvo de Boer, called "the big picture."
It shows the ground plan for a possible agreement in which the industrialised nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent in the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community has also given a boost to Friday's talks by promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change, from mastering floods and droughts to avoiding deforestation.
Friday nevertheless brought the same verbal fireworks that had determined the talks last week.
The US Special Representative for Climate Action Todd Stern has rejected formulations that demand binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialised countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging economies, if not financed by the industrialised nations.
This train announced that the Obama administration was driving a tougher line with China than representatives of the Bush administration less than two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without major emerging economies getting up and taking action, said Stern, who also complained that the text would not go far enough to ensure that the reductions could also be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern gave his statement one hour after the statement of Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei, which said that the leading American climate negotiator either lacks "reason" or it was "highly irresponsible" of him that he said at the beginning of the week that the United States would not help China financially to cope with global warming.
As the future economic direction of the great world powers is at stake, break lines have opened up both within the industrialized nations and between the industrialized nations and the emerging economies.
The current struggle relates equally to the rescue of individual economies, as well as the rescue of the planet, with China and the United States fighting for their corresponding commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take more courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a Costa Rican delegate, said that it is not surprising that the great powers are fighting for who should bear the cost of curbing greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have gone more aggressively to hold the countries with very high greenhouse gas emissions accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game from which a new economic supremacy will develop, says Ulate, who is also working as a regional climate change advisor for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the effects of climate change stated that they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although the leading participants say that the talks will at best lead to a political agreement.
The alliance of small island states with 43 members presented a 24-page draft treaty early on Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the offensive of small island states "puts political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now united and demand action from emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks were given a new urgency when delegates focused on the fact that most of the open questions had to be resolved before the leaders arrived to reach an agreement.
High-ranking representatives, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Vice Minister, stepped off their planes and rushed through the corridors of the Bella Center to meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to cover claims that will be negotiated during the next week.
The sheer scale of the gathering -- 13,000 people enter and leave the convention center every day, gitarre-playing activists hold night shows in which they make fun of the countries that they think are betraying and selling, and draft contracts are handed over from hand to hand instead of by e-mail -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just building up: almost all the important ministers are here now and from Wednesday 60 leaders will be in Copenhagen.
We're coming to the Oberliga, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice President for Global Policy of Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
