Manager Revolution or the End of Strategic Early Enlightenment?
If nothing changes in the leadership of the great French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence has been in vain ...
For over a decade, the attitude of managing large companies in relation to its employees, said the position of companies vis-à-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: It is for the staff to join "values" determined the best as it used to be to impose on consumer products designed by the technicians at the factory.
By placing the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution has given the strategies of conquering the markets in the place ... although the authoritarian temptation products separate factors to impose customer preferences again regularly!
Demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
The suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of a much bigger phenomenon that touches employees in particular.
This demobilization has a negative impact on the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially those of R&E and, more importantly, those of economic intelligence.
In fact, IE (Intelligence Economique = Economic Intelligence) calls for "a proactive approach and a forward-looking view from all parties involved"; it demands from the employees an effort that is entirely contrary to the instructions of authoritarian management.
That is why we are calling for an operational revolution that would consist of placing employees at the centre of the company's concerns alongside customers on an equal footing.
The very conditional benefit of internal opinion polls
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire that Orange submitted to its wage earners, stimulate this revolution in terms of management practice?
I'm afraid not.
First of all, because I was able to see that, in the face of a new situation after many detours, the whole structure eventually comes to do as a matter of priority what it has always done.
Also because authoritarianism - one of the pathologies of power - increases proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
And finally, because most executives have a much simplified conception of human behavior.
From the large engineering schools their interpretation of psychology is mechanistic.
Through intellectual comfort, they adopt the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the American "Neurosciences" and unknowingly widely disseminated by research institutes and the media.
Thus, and by suggesting that it is possible to use the "hebel" (sic) to engage employees, a recent survey by Ipsos published by Le Figaro.fr strengthens the managers in an attitude towards a mechanistic control system that is unsuitable for today's world.
Identifying and measuring the mobilisation factors
Instead, an operational revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises presupposes the adoption of a definitive view of human behaviour.
It consists of integrating a fundamental protocol into any consideration or practice of governance: for the wage earners, the commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to realize part of their dreams, ambition and projects.
At the moment, only the studies from the multifunctional analysis take over this concept of motivation of the employees.
These studies have shown that they judge their company on the basis of a predetermined doxa, which allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to assess what it offers them to achieve their life goals.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of these mobilisation factors, the managers of the companies can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and place their human resource management back in the right place.
In this way, they create a fertile soil that is favourable for the coordinated development of a robust and efficient economic intelligence.
The Oslo speech: the "just war" brings praise to Obama from the right
The American Right welcomed Barack Obama's speech in Oslo on Friday and was pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
The conservatives who mocked the award to Obama on 9 October applauded the President's speech this time, following the example of the former Vice Presidential candidate in the 2008 elections, Sarah Palin.
