Long-distance drivers: Three marathons for an agreement that secures the supply for Christmas
After a three-week negotiation marathon, the trade unions of the Road Association and the TLF - the only employer organisation that remained until the end - came to an agreement on Friday evening that put an end to the strike order and the imminent heavy supply shortage at Christmas.
At the signature meeting on Friday evening, the State Secretary in charge of transport, Dominique Bussereau, welcomed the agreement, which was launched on Wednesday morning after several weeks of negotiations.
After a second night of negotiations, the negotiators broke up early on Friday morning hoping to sign the agreement quickly in the late morning.
And even though the three employers' associations (FNTR, Unostra and OTRE) had left the meeting upset.
However, more than six hours passed from the beginning of the meeting at 11:00 until the conclusion of the agreement, and the agreement was signed only at 18:00.
The conflict "had done a great deal of damage to the companies" and "it was to be feared that it would affect the holidays at the end of the year," said Bussereau.
The agreement provides for a 4% wage increase for the lowest wages (local and regional road transport) and 2.9% for the highest wage groups (international transports).
The hourly rate for employees with the lowest wages therefore rises from 8.72 euros to 9.06 euros.
"That's not very much, but we'll start small," says Patrice Clos (FO).
Activists are now instructed not to block the supply centres.
"However, there will probably always be some unruly people who are not satisfied with the agreement," he adds.
TLF chairman Philippe Grillot spoke of a "good agreement" although it was "difficult to grant these wage increases in the face of international competition".
According to him, the increase is 170 euros per month for the low and 100 to 120 euros for the high wage groups.
"This agreement is based on common sense and respect for employees," said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) spoke of "a historic agreement".
Richard Jaubert (CGT) commented on "an acceptable compromise".
