Turkish Constitutional Court dissolves pro-Kurdish party. Decision with serious consequences
On Friday, the Turkish Constitutional Court announced the dissolution of the country's pro-Kurdish main party, a decision immediately followed by angry demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and Istanbul.
This decision threatens to complicate the work of the government, which is trying to reach out to the Kurdish community in order to put an end to the conflicts that have been going on for 25 years.
The "party for a democratic society" (DTP) was dissolved as it had become a "place for activities that are detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity", said the President of the Constitutional Court Hasim Kiliç four days after the decision to the press.
According to Kiliç, the decision would have been taken unanimously by 11 judges, with a majority of seven votes required to impose the dissolution. He also pointed out that 37 of the party's leaders, including Chairman Ahmet Türk and parliamentarian Aysel Tugluk, were excluded from the political process for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the waiver of parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Turk and Tugluk, as well as the confiscation of the party's goods.
The DTP now has 21 seats in Parliament (from 550).
Before the verdict, the party leaders said that parliamentarians would rather leave Parliament than meet like non-partisan parliamentarians.
The decision followed a trial initiated in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Turkish federal court Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya. He accused the DTP of following the "consecrations" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which Ankara and many other countries regard as a terrorist organization.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party assures that it has "no connection" with the PKK, but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate.
The verdict of the Constitutional Court is intervening with the government, which is seeking to meet the Kurdish community and propose a series of measures to strengthen the rights of the Kurds in order to make the support of the PKK by the Kurds dry up and put an end to the conflicts.
The leaders of the DTP reaffirm that a resolution could lead to a re-emergence of tensions in Southeast Anatolia, where numerous demonstrations against the detention conditions of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan had led to clashes with the police in recent weeks.
Since the court's announcement, thousands of demonstrators have gathered in front of the DTP's premises in Diyarbakir, a city in the south-east, which is predominantly populated by Kurds.
The forces of order used tear gas grenades and water cannons when the demonstrators started throwing Molotov cocktails and stones.
Hundreds of people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Türk assumed that the court's decision "will deepen despair even further".
"Turkey cannot resolve this (Kurdish, ed.) issue on the basis of a party's ban," he told the press.
The government, consisting of a party that emerged from the Islamist movement, also regretted the decision.
"We oppose the closure of the parties on principle.
