The cradle of dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: the two-meter long and 1.50-meter-sized animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, bent teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science of Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in today's New Mexico, which at that time was in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangäa on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window on the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us much about the relationship, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began digging at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Triassic, team member Randall Irmis reports from the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones were quickly identified as a new species.
During the excavation, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
Find confirms theories about Dino's early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only single fragments can be found."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share enthusiasm.
This find is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current doctrine, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these Ur-Dinos is mostly controversial.
For example, the experts discuss when the lizards split into their three most important lines of development: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds known as the "long necks", the four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and the plant-eating Ornithischia (bird basin dinosaurs), which included, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of airbags, such as the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the huge sauropods later also had airbags and lightweight bones, the common ancestor of both groups had probably already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards appeared there for the first time.
Thus, the three development lines separated early and spread from South America over all parts of the world, which at that time still formed a single land mass as Supercontinent Pangäa.
This is due to the fact that the team, together with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
The researchers argue that the three cannot descend from a common, immigrated ancestor.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could be distorted, because in South America especially many primitive Dino fossils have been preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to be found.
How the dinosaurs managed to develop from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile tribe to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Earth's Middle Ages is still puzzling.
During the Triassic period, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and flight dinosaurs and numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic, the dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while the relatives died out at the border from the Triassic to the Jura.
Success story didn't last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass death that the dinosaurs happened to survive, but the other reptiles didn't.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so that they could beat the competition out of the field.
In any case, the success story did not last forever.
150 million years later a meteorite impact helped a group of animals to bloom, which had also developed in the Triassic and since then a shadow existence lasted: the mammals.
