Dream Worlds
Some see images in a awake state and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
The boundaries between imagination and reality are blurred not only in the case of the mentally ill and in the drug rush.
As long as it happens in your sleep, everything's fine.
When we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can give ourselves uninhibited to the wildest ideas and imaginations.
However, in the modern Western world, those who experience dreamlike states, see and hear things that others do not see or hear, are usually regarded as crazy or drug addicts, at least as special.
But such images and voices arise not only from the mentally ill or from the drug rush.
Our imagination is to blame: the same neural processes that enable us to design houses, paint pictures, or write novels sometimes make the boundaries between dream, delusion, and reality blur.
Dreamlike altered waking consciousness states can occur in the most different forms, in the best case we call them visions, in the worst case delusion.
Although triggers and effects may differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic rapture states, psychosis and hallucinations can be traced back to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neuronal messenger substances of the brain - above all dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholine - is derailed and the interaction of different parts of the brain is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts are very common during schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity no longer has power over him
The connection between delusion and dream has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived hallucinations as a form of dream in the awake state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, stated in 1861 a "great resemblance of madness with dream states", for Sigmund Freud the dream was "a psychosis, with all inconsistencies, delusions, delusions of the senses of such".
It is autumn 2001 when Henning T. turns into a comic figure.
His body is two-dimensional and squeaky.
Gravity no longer has any power over him, it floats on the ceiling.
He feels a kick.
Behind him winged devil figures with blood red, distorted faces, teething.
They hunt him down, kick him with heavy, flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels the pain all over his body.
Loud, vicious voices roar out of walls and radio.
He can't stand them anymore, the voices that insult and insult him.
Henning T. pulls two cables from the stereo, knots them to a loop and attaches them to a hook on the ceiling.
He gets on a speaker and puts the noose around his neck.
Jump.
The noose is loosening.
This is supposed to be a lesson to you, the voices scream in a drum-feeling choir, "Go to the clinic and let yourself be healed!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last is 2 years ago, the first almost 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
His diagnosis is schizoaffective paranoid psychosis, and he's manic-depressive, he's taking drugs against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, for three years he has been married.
In psychosis, I have experienced the worst fear and deepest despair, he says.
The deceptive images are cruel reality
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in life, and in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, sufferers can usually no longer distinguish between the inside and the outside world, they get into an overexcited state that can lead to hallucinations, megalomania, relationship or persecution.
Voice listening is particularly common - voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also not uncommon.
The affected person can no longer separate important things from unimportant things, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like the dream, the psychosis opens the locks to a flood of ideas and fantasies that come from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician at the Department of General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is in the center of the event, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, like in a dream, he gets overwhelmed by the events and cannot actively shape them.
Therefore, schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
A reality balance is usually not possible for them, the deceptive images are cruel reality, waking up excluded.
To have experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, "but the sensual and spatial structure of reality perceived in the psychosis remains fundamentally preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based in reality, the alienation of the experience takes place within the real framework.
Why exactly our brain beats capriols is still a mystery for researchers.
In every human being, exceptional states can cause him to lose the reference to reality for a short time, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that genes are not the sole determinants.
Researchers assume that there is minimal brain damage in patients.
We suspect that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disturbed at an early stage of development, for example by a mother's viral disease during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains a mystery how the disorder of the neural system comes about, which does not manifest itself at all for many years at first.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be the trigger for a psychosis when the disposition is present.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also trigger psychosis as they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brain is hot
The crazy thing is, psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, others spend money on drugs to get them, says Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether false images are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often only a question of position.
Kasten has been collecting reports about hallucinations and deceptions for ten years, and last year he evaluated his results in the book "The Unreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations belong to the typical side effects of psychosis, but also to an astonishing number of other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often include diseases such as migraines, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's disease and cranial brain trauma.
Surprisingly, even the brain of healthy people hallucinates under certain conditions.
Hallucinations, according to box, are made up of memory contents that are usually held back.
They arise when brain areas in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or too little inhibited; when our brain is hot or even when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can cause this condition as much as brain damage or psychosis.
But also irritation, stress, heartache or other mental exceptional states.
In recent studies, up to a third of respondents reported having experienced hallucination at least once in life.
In summer 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends the Gymnasium there.
A normal girl, actually.
If it weren't for the pictures and voices.
During the break it may happen that a sloppy boy with long, dark hair will respond to it.
When it answers him, the classmates look at it surprised - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a spun daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't dream, she knows that.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bank next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for moments.
A pleasant feeling is that she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? she asks herself sometimes.
But she knows that this boy and the other delusions are not real and disappear again.
At night, the apparitions are usually frightening
Often the false images are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she sometimes cannot follow the teaching material, because the teacher in her eyes and ears is just introducing a new fellow student, while he explains mathematical equations for all the others, both audible and visible, on the board.
At night, the apparitions are usually frightening.
When she waits for sleep in her dark room, which is far too rare and far too late, she often cannot tell whether she is awake or already dreams, whether the pictures she sees are the frats or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she screams at the figures.
Parents and friends don't tell her they think she's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She graduated from high school last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she got in touch with the psychologist box on the Internet, she knows she's not crazy.
Delusion is also a work of art of despair
If someone is socially isolated or suffers from irritation, he is likely to have hallucinations after a while, says Kasten.
I guess the brain's understaffed, and it's his own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13 that the man she calls Papa has not been her physical father since she could think.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and sounds, it is difficult for those affected, such as Sarah K., to distinguish between false images and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, where reality takes place.
Hallucinations are also images that create the brain, which is why they seem so real."
Even nightly dream pictures see box as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their false images as unreal.
Therefore, caste advises his patients to value the hallucinations as a special ability.
Limit state between dream and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our too much conscious world, imaginary experience is usually pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a severe, painful illness, but it also contains positive, creative delusion, which is also a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched the so-called oneiroide experience form, a special form of the dreamlike altered waking consciousness.
Oneiroide are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams, which the experiencer considers to be real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking state even in hindsight.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in trauma or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a human being is threatened with self- and world loss, for example by persistent, complete mobility, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
It's kind of a borderline between dream and hallucination.
Since coping with a situation in reality is not possible, a world change takes place, but the real situation is present in the imagination.
An intensive form of meaning and meaning in an in itself intolerable situation, which enables us humans to not sink into a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his Oneiroid experiences in his book "Heart Change" as a rescue action of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve operation followed by a heart transplant, while his body in the intensive care unit is condemned to lack of movement.
Claussen dives into a self-created world, visiting strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden old man, aboard a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among noblemen who produce intoxicants from blood.
If a Greek takes a motorcycle to his home country, surf with his hospital bed in the firn snow of the Alps and meet a Korean mafioso.
He goes on completely in the imagined event, everything is real, even later in the memory.
These inner journeys are fundamentally different for Claussen from every dream.
Dream is a different state, he describes his experience.
In contrast to this, the memories from mental journeys are clear to me after years and in minor details.
Clearer and more intense even than really experienced ones.
The intensity of this experience goes beyond the horizon of our other life-worldly experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
In the end, Oneiroide, psychosis, hallucinations and drug rush show how fragile our inner images of outer reality are in the guard.
Any change in the state of consciousness, sums up the psychologist's box, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
