75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who wish to have children.
This is the conclusion of the study "Fruitability and career of women in Spain" carried out by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9.737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities in the labour market limited due to their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are large differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether women work or not and, if so, what kind of profession they do.
Those of them who do no other work outside the house, work only half-days or have no fixed employment contract become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, the women with a permanent job, especially in the public sector, postpone the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore also have fewer children.
"Women in the age group between 35 and 49 years of age with a permanent job will only get their first child on average 3.7 years after moving in together, a number which increases to 4.1 years for women with a permanent job, who have taken longer to achieve this and who have moved in and realized the first child much later.
In addition, the type of work also has a major influence on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar of conception," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that needs to be taken into account in the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference could also be noted for women of the same age.
For example, women in the group aged between 35 and 49, depending on whether they only have a secondary education or a higher education, became mothers on average at 25,1 or 32,1 for the first time.
There is also a further difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While the women with the main degree already get married before their first permanent job and have their first child, the women with a middle or high school degree do it exactly the other way around and first find a permanent job and get married afterwards and then have their first child, notes Delgado.
