Support for braking maneuvers in critical situations is now mandatory
As in the case of the ABS anti-lock braking system at that time, and as is currently happening with the ESP stability control system, emergency braking systems must become mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are mandatory for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans, and for the remaining vehicles a waiting period has been set until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure adopted by the European Union is to improve the protection of pedestrians, but due to its operation these braking systems can also help to prevent many collisions.
The task of the emergency braking assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking manoeuvre, which the system detects on the brake pedal, based on the braking strength specified by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, one third of the drivers involved in an accident did not even get to step on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not braked with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The braking aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system and thus reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car travels during the braking process.
According to an EU study, every year up to 1,100 fatal accidents causing damage to pedestrians could be prevented if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents - it is expected that one in four accidents could be prevented with personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, the system helps him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is inevitable, the brake assistant exerts the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
